DOCREF="AP880927-0117"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Canadians were shamed, angry, and saddened that national hero Ben
Johnson was stripped of his Olympic gold medal after a urine sample
showed traces of anabolic steroids.  Johnson had won the 100-meter
dash in a record-breaking 9.79 seconds.  The medal went to American
Carl Lewis who finished second.  Canada's Sports Minister said his
government accepted the validity of the tests.  He acknowledged that
it was suggested to him several months ago that Johnson might be using
steroids.  It was a second shock to national sports fans after hockey
legend Wayne Gretsky was traded from the Edmonton Oilers to the Los
Angeles Kings.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880928-0146"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

The stripping of Ben Johnson's Olympic gold medal after he won the 100
meters Saturday in 9.79 seconds, shamed a nation hungry for a hero to
replace hockey superstar Wayne Gretsky.  He was stripped of the medal
Tuesday when he tested positive for stanzolol, a steroid outlawed by
Olympic officials.  Sports columnists heralded his unheroic conduct as
"Fools Gold", "From Fame to Shame", and "Big Ben is Now Has Been",
calling the episode a tragedy of epic proportions.  However, one
columnist said the nation should not cover its head in shame noting
that after all, "it is also just a foot race."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881009-0072" 
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Fellow Canadian Olympic sprinter Angella Issajenko was quoted as
saying in a published interview that Ben Johnson knowingly took
steroids.  She also said that Johnson, stripped of his Olympic gold
medal in the 100-meter final after testing positive for stanzolol, was
also taking steroids when he set a world sprint record last summer in
Rome.  Ms. Issajenko said she also took the muscle-building drugs and
claimed that Dr. Jamie Astaphan provided the steroids to her and
Johnson with the knowledge of their track coach.  The federal
government has appointed an official to head a judicial inquiry into
the Johnson affair.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA021689-0227"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Ben Johnson's personal physician, Dr. Jamie Astaphan, has said that
the disgraced sprinter took the banned steroid stanzolol on one
occasion four months before the Seoul Olympics last year.  Astaphan
said Johnson suffered "violent muscle spasms" after taking it and that
he nursed him back to top condition.  Astaphan also said that Johnson
was not on stanzolol when he beat Lewis for the 100 meters gold and
denied he ever prescribed such drugs to Johnson or other athletes.
Johnson has said he never knowingly took performance-enhancing drugs.
An inquiry into drug use in amateur sports resumes hearing next
Wednesday in Toronto.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
