SUMMARIZER="G">      

In the aftermath of Ben Johnson admitting to his steroid use, many US
track and field officials and athletes said Johnson should be stripped
of his world record in the 100-meter dash.  Johnson testified this
week at a Canadian inquiry that his involvement with illegal
performance- enhancing drugs included injections before the 1987 World
Championships in Rome.  He was tested after his world-record run
there, but the results were negative.  The possibility that Johnson
could lose his record was raised when the International Amateur
Athletic Federation asked for "legal opinion" to see what to do about
records of confessed drug users.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA030789-0047"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Carl Lewis said he knew Ben Johnson was taking performance-enhancing
drugs just after their 100-meter final at the Seoul Olympics.  Now
Lewis has been implicated in an alleged sabotage of Johnson's drug
test, which turned out positive.  A Canadian sprint coach testified at
a Canadian inquiry that Johnson might have drunk contaminated beer
before a urine analysis.  Accordingly, an unidentified man who had
been talking with Lewis sat near the beer provided to facilitate urine
samples.  Lewis' attorney said the allocation was ludicrous.  Lewis
called for Johnson to be a role model like himself and to tell kids to
stay off drugs.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA030889-0163"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Lynda Huey, who was at the Seoul Olympics working for NBC-TV and as a
physical therapist, said that Canadian coach Charlie Francis bragged
about Ben Johnson's preparation for a show- down against sprinter Carl
Lewis.  Accordingly, Francis, who had claimed that Johnson's urine
sample at the Olympics was spiked with a banned steroid, told Ms. Huey
before the race that Johnson was "more afraid of failing the drug test
than he is of Carl Lewis."  Huey said at a drug use inquiry she had
known Francis since 1980 and she was tired of hearing him say Johnson
was clean at the Olympics.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891006-0029"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Ben Johnson, the world-class sprinter who lost his Olympic gold medal
after testing positive for steroids, said that it is wrong for
athletes to use muscle-building substances.  Johnson spoke to
reporters as legislation to classify anabolic steroids as a controlled
substance was introduced Thursday.  He was invited to appear by three
Congressmen who were presenting the legislation.  Carl Lewis also
attended the news conference because he was working on his
autobiography and one of his chapters deals with steroids.
Representative Mel Levine (D-Calif) referred to the abuse of steroids
as "the silent side of the drug disease in this country."</SUM>

<SUM
