Ben Johnson will at last get his chance to back up his boasts that he
can regain his form of two years ago (1988) when he was stripped of
his 100-meter gold medal after testing positive for anabolic steroids.
His two-year suspension ends today and the questions begin - What can
he do when not assisted by drugs?  Promoters of indoor meets this
season are anxious to sign him up for high fees in the hope that his
promises to redeem himself will fill seats and rejuvenate interest in
track.  Johnson has passed at least four drug tests during his
suspension.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06012224"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

In the 50-meter dash at the Hamilton Spectator Games Friday, the first
race after his two-year suspension for drug use, Ben Johnson proved he
can run fast without the prohibited anabolic steroid that caused his
expulsion.  However, he only managed to finish second behind Darn
Council of Florida.  The race produced a record crowd of 17,050 and
drew nearly 500 journalists from 14 countries.  His time of 5.77
seconds to Council's 5.75 was far from the 5.55 he ran in 1987 that is
still the fastest ever.  Johnson was given a thunderous standing
ovation before and after the race.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06084228"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Charlie Francis, the Canadian National Sprint Coach, testifying in
Toronto at a federal inquiry about the use of performance-enhancing
drugs, made it plain that he had given the athletes every steroid
combination imaginable, his experiments carefully calibrated and
analyzed.  His system worked well until his most famous pupil, Ben
Johnson, tested positive for illegal steroid use at the Seoul Olympics
in 1988 and lost his gold medal.  In his own confessional "Speed
Trap", Francis argues that steroids must be used to be a world-class
sprinter.  They make runners train harder not run harder, their use is
rampant, and too prevalent to be banned.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d31"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880928-0054"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Ben Johnson returned to Canada without the Olympic gold
medal, dodging reporters and the public and refusing to
talk about the illegal steroid found in his system after he
won the 100-meter dash as the world's fastest human.  On
the flight from South Korea, he denied using the drugs
although Olympic officials said the results were
indisputable.  Canada's Sports Minister said Johnson tested
negative for drugs in August and passed eight tests in two
years.  Johnson's family, friends, and personal physician
denied he took steroids.  Hundreds rallied to his side in
Toronto but his fans in Montreal said they were
disappointed.</SUM>    
